✅ What Actually Happens During Certificate Rollover

Using Active Directory Federation Services as example:

🔁 Before Expiration (Grace Period)

1️⃣ ADFS generates a new signing certificate
2️⃣ Metadata now contains:

Old certificate

New certificate
3️⃣ IdP may still sign with the old certificate initially
4️⃣ Later, IdP switches to signing with the new certificate

🏗 What Rails Should Do (Correct Behavior)

If using ruby-saml properly:

Rails loads metadata

Stores both certificates

During verification:

Try cert 1

If fails → try cert 2

If one passes → accept

So yes ✅ verification works with either.

❗ First Small Correction

You said:

once new certificate is available we will configure new certificate

That depends on setup.

There are 2 cases:

🔹 Static setup

You manually update Rails with new certificate.

🔹 Metadata-driven setup (better)

Rails automatically loads both certs from metadata.

In modern enterprise setups → metadata-driven is preferred.

❗ Second Small Correction (Important One)

You said:

when expiration passed, metadata will stop sending old certificate and our old certificate verify signature fails and new certificate verification passes and now rails remove new certificate

The last part is slightly wrong.

It should be:

Metadata removes OLD certificate.

Rails refreshes metadata.

Rails removes OLD certificate.

Rails continues trusting NEW certificate.

You do NOT remove the new certificate.

You remove the expired one.

🔐 Final Correct Flow
Phase 1 – Before rotation

Metadata:

OLD_CERT

Rails trusts:

OLD_CERT
Phase 2 – Rollover period

Metadata:

OLD_CERT
NEW_CERT

Rails trusts:

OLD_CERT
NEW_CERT

IdP signs with either (usually switches gradually).

Phase 3 – After expiration

Metadata:

NEW_CERT

Rails refreshes metadata → now trusts:

NEW_CERT only

Everything continues smoothly.

🚨 What Would Break It?

If:

Rails only had OLD_CERT

IdP switches to NEW_CERT

Rails never refreshed metadata

Then:

❌ Signature validation fails
❌ All SSO logins break

